 Here is an example of how to automatically generate a table of contents in a LATEX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{tocloft} % required for setting toc depth
\setcounter{tocdepth}{2} % sets depth of TOC to display sections and subsections

\usepackage{hyperref} % required for linking in-document references 

\usepackage{titlesec} % required for fancy section formatting
\titleformat{\section}[hang]{\normalfont\Large\bfseries}{\thesection}{1em}{} 
\titleformat{\subsection}[hang]{\normalfont\normalsize\bfseries}{\thesubsection}{1em}{}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % Prints the table of contents

\section{Section 1} 
\subsection{Subsection 1}

\subsection{Subsection 2}

\section{Section 2}  
Some text...

\end{document}
```

This will produce a table of contents with links to the sections and subsections, with a depth of 2 (meaning it shows sections and subsections). The `tocloft` package is used to set the depth. The `hyperref` package provides the linking functionality. The `titlesec` package is used here just to format the section headings, but is not required for the TOC generation.

The `\tableofcontents` command simply needs to be placed where you want the TOC to appear, and LATEX will automatically generate it from the sectioning commands used in the document.

