 Here is a solution in Java:

```java
public class QueueUsingStacks {
    private Stack<Integer> stack1 = new Stack<>();
    private Stack<Integer> stack2 = new Stack<>();

    public void add(int element) {
        stack1.push(element);
    }

    public int remove() {
        if (stack2.isEmpty()) {
            while (!stack1.isEmpty()) {
                stack2.push(stack1.pop());
            }
        } 
        return stack2.pop();
    }

    public int peek() {
        if (stack2.isEmpty()) {
            while (!stack1.isEmpty()) {
                stack2.push(stack1.pop());
            }
        } 
        return stack2.peek();
    }

    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return stack1.isEmpty() && stack2.isEmpty();
    }
}
```

This implements a queue using two stacks. The add() method simply pushes to stack1. The remove() and peek() methods first check if stack2 is empty. If so, all elements from stack1 are popped and pushed to stack2. Then the top element of stack2 is popped/peeked. The isEmpty() method checks if both stacks are empty.

