 Here is a Java solution to find the longest common subsequence between two strings:
```java
public class LongestCommonSubsequence {
    public String lcs(String str1, String str2) {
        int[][] dp = new int[str1.length() + 1][str2.length() + 1];

        for (int i = 1; i <= str1.length(); i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j <= str2.length(); j++) {
                if (str1.charAt(i - 1) == str2.charAt(j - 1)) {
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1;
                } else {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1]);
                }
            }
        }

        StringBuilder lcs = new StringBuilder();
        int i = str1.length(), j = str2.length();
        while (i > 0 && j > 0) {
            if (str1.charAt(i - 1) == str2.charAt(j - 1)) {
                lcs.append(str1.charAt(i - 1));
                i--;
                j--;
            } else if (dp[i - 1][j] > dp[i][j - 1]) {
                i--;
            } else {
                j--;
            }
        }

        return lcs.reverse().toString();
    }
}
```

This uses a bottom-up dynamic programming approach. We build a 2D array dp where dp[i][j] represents the length of the LCS of str1.substring(0, i) and str2.substring(0, j). We fill this array row by row, and in each cell we take the maximum of:

1. The LCS of str1.substring(0, i - 1) and str2.substring(0, j - 1) plus 1 (if the last characters match) 
2. The LCS of str1.substring(0, i - 1) and str2.substring(0, j) 
3. The LCS of str1.substring(0, i) and str2.substring(0, j - 1)

Once the array is filled, we trace back from the bottom-right cell to build the actual LCS string.

The time complexity of this solution is O(m*n) where m and n are the lengths of the input strings.

 Here is a solution in Java:
```java
public int[] productExceptSelf(int[] nums) {
    int[] output = new int[nums.length];
    int product = 1;

    // Compute product of all elements to the left
    for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
        output[i] = product;
        product *= nums[i];
    }

    // Compute product of all elements to the right
    product = 1;
    for (int i = nums.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        output[i] *= product;
        product *= nums[i];
    }

    return output;
}
```

This solves it in two passes:

1. First pass: Compute the product of all elements to the left of each element. Store in output array.
2. Second pass: Compute the product of all elements to the right of each element. Multiply with the previously computed product and store in output array.

So for the example input [1,2,3,4], the output array will be:

- output[0] = 1 x 2 x 3 x 4 = 24 
- output[1] = 1 x 3 x 4 = 12
- output[2] = 1 x 4 = 8
- output[3] = 6

Time complexity: O(n) since we do two passes of n elements. 
Space complexity: O(1) since we use a fixed size output array.

