The shortest distance between the two circles is the distance between their closest points.  The closest points will occur where the line connecting the circle centers is tangent to both circles.  The center of the first circle is $(12, 16)$ and the center of the second circle is $(-12, -16)$.  The slope of the line connecting these points is \begin{align*} m &= \frac{16-(-16)}{12-(-12)} = \frac{32}{24} = \boxed{4/3} \end{align*}
Using the point-slope form, the equation of this line is \begin{align*} (y-16) &= \frac43(x-12)\\ \\Rightarrow\\qquad y&= \frac43x - 32 \end{align*}
The tangent points must satisfy the circle equations.  Substituting the line equation into the first circle's equation gives \begin{align*} (x-12)^2 + (y-16)^2 &= 24^2\\ \\Rightarrow\\qquad (x-12)^2 + \left(\frac43x - 32\right)^2 &= 576 \end{align*}
